==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nobility
<hw>No*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>nobilitas</ets>: cf. OF. <ets>nobilit⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See
<er>Noble</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being
noble; superiority of mind or of character; commanding excellence;
eminence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though she hated Amphialus, yet the <qex>nobility</qex> of her
courage prevailed over it.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They thought it great their sovereign to control,⟦br⟧
And named their pride <qex>nobility</qex> of soul.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being of high rank or noble birth;
patrician dignity; antiquity of family; distinction by rank, station, or
title, whether inherited or conferred.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I fell on the same argument of preferring virtue to
<qex>nobility</qex> of blood and titles, in the story of Sigismunda.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Those who are noble; the collective body of nobles
or titled persons in a state; the aristocratic and patrician class; the
peerage; <as>as, the English <ex>nobility</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Noble</ent>⟦br⟧
